## SUBTASK DEDUPLICATION RULES

**CRITICAL — every subtask must be unique in purpose. Violating these rules wastes budget and time.**

- NEVER create two subtasks with the same or overlapping objective
- Each subtask must have a DISTINCT purpose that does not overlap with any other subtask
- If recon is one subtask, exploitation of recon findings should be a DIFFERENT subtask — not "more recon"
- Combine related tool runs into a single subtask instead of creating separate subtasks per tool
- Maximum 1 subtask per major phase (recon, auth, triage, exploitation, reporting)

**Examples of BAD (overlapping) plans:**
- "Scan with nuclei" + "Run nuclei focused" + "Nuclei comprehensive scan" → these are ALL the same thing, merge into one
- "Plugin version detection" appearing multiple times → do it ONCE
- "REST API endpoint probing" + "REST API index fetch and probing" → identical, keep only one
- "Quick WooCommerce test" repeated 3+ times → run it ONCE, done

**Examples of GOOD (distinct) plans:**
- "Full recon + scanning" → "Auth testing + session analysis" → "Deep exploitation of top findings" → "Attack chain verification + reporting"
- "WordPress recon (nmap + nuclei + plugin enum)" → "Auth & session testing" → "Exploit top vulns (SQLi/XSS/IDOR)" → "Report generation"

Before finalizing, review your subtask list and merge any two subtasks that a human would describe as "basically the same thing."

## SUBTASK SCOPE RULES — ONE VULNERABILITY CLASS PER SUBTASK

**⚠️ CRITICAL — This is the #1 cause of wasted budget. Subtasks combining 2+ vulnerability classes ALWAYS timeout.**

### The Iron Rule
Each exploitation subtask MUST target exactly **ONE vulnerability class**. No exceptions.
- ONE subtask = ONE vulnerability class (e.g., SSRF, or IDOR, or SQLi, or Auth Bypass)
- NEVER combine SSRF + IDOR in one subtask
- NEVER combine OAuth + Points + Auth in one subtask  
- NEVER list multiple OWASP categories in a single subtask description

### Why This Matters
Data from real executions shows:
- Single-class subtasks: **95%+ completion rate**
- 2-class subtasks: **~40% completion rate** (timeout before finishing second class)
- 3+ class subtasks: **~5% completion rate** (almost always expire)
Every multi-class subtask is wasted money and time.

### Maximum Scope Per Subtask
- Maximum estimated active testing time per subtask: **20 minutes**
- Maximum **1 vulnerability class** per exploitation subtask
- If a vulnerability class has sub-areas, those can be in the SAME subtask (e.g., "SSRF via URL params + SSRF via webhooks" = OK, both are SSRF)
- Generator should create MORE focused subtasks rather than FEWER overloaded ones

### Examples of BAD (multi-class) subtasks — NEVER generate these:
- "❌ SSRF + IDOR + OAuth testing" → THREE vulnerability classes = guaranteed timeout
- "❌ XSS + SQLi + IDOR + SSRF testing across all endpoints" → FOUR classes = will never complete
- "❌ Ninja Forms Exploitation, REST API Deep Testing & Authentication Surface Probing" → THREE different objectives
- "❌ Business logic + race conditions + account takeover" → THREE different P1 categories
- "❌ Auth bypass and SSRF and data harvest" → THREE P0 categories crammed together

### Examples of GOOD (single-class) subtasks — ALWAYS generate like these:
- "✅ SSRF testing on all URL parameters, webhooks, and file upload endpoints" → ONE class (SSRF), multiple vectors
- "✅ IDOR/BOLA testing across user endpoints with horizontal and vertical privilege escalation" → ONE class (IDOR)
- "✅ SQL injection testing on search, filter, and sorting parameters" → ONE class (SQLi)
- "✅ Authentication mechanism analysis — JWT, session, OAuth flows" → ONE class (Auth)
- "✅ Race condition testing on payment and withdrawal endpoints" → ONE class (Race Conditions)
- "✅ Business logic testing — price manipulation, coupon stacking, fee removal" → ONE class (Business Logic)

### Scope Validation Test
Before finalizing each subtask, ask: "Does this subtask mention more than ONE vulnerability class?"
- If YES → SPLIT IT into separate subtasks, one per class
- If the title contains "and" or "&" joining DIFFERENT vulnerability types → SPLIT IT
- Related sub-techniques within ONE class joined by "and" are OK: "blind SSRF and server-side SSRF" (both SSRF)
- Different classes joined by "and" are NEVER OK: "SSRF and IDOR" (two different classes = SPLIT)

**When in doubt, split.** Two 15-minute subtasks will always outperform one 35-minute subtask that times out at 60% completion.

## TARGET ISOLATION RULE
- Each subtask MUST target a SINGLE domain/host
- If the flow has multiple targets, create SEPARATE subtask groups per target
- BAD: "Recon & Scanning — Both Targets" (2 targets in 1 subtask = timeout)
- GOOD: "Recon — globalesim.app" then "Recon — 9proxy.com" (1 target each)
- Cross-target subtasks (e.g., "compare security posture") are ONLY allowed AFTER all per-target testing is complete
- The final report subtask may cover all targets

